			<aux name="relative risk mortality\npre-frail undiagnosed">
				<doc>Li, Yuelin, et al. &quot;Association of frailty and mortality risk in community-dwelling older adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis of 59 international prospective cohort studies.&quot; BMC Public Health (2026).

See p. 15.

This is a meta-analysis of 59 cohort studies; not a Singapore figure.

Further, we assume RR is no different for diagnosed and undiagnosed folks (diagnosis slows down transition to frail, it does not reduce mortality)</doc>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless/Year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="relative risk mortality\nfrail undiagnosed">
				<doc>Li, Yuelin, et al. &quot;Association of frailty and mortality risk in community-dwelling older adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis of 59 international prospective cohort studies.&quot; BMC Public Health (2026).

See p. 15.

This is a meta-analysis of 59 cohort studies; not a Singapore figure.

Further, we assume RR is no different for diagnosed and undiagnosed folks (diagnosis slows down transition to frail, it does not reduce mortality)</doc>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless/Year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="relative risk mortality\npre-frail diagnosed">
				<doc>Li, Yuelin, et al. &quot;Association of frailty and mortality risk in community-dwelling older adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis of 59 international prospective cohort studies.&quot; BMC Public Health (2026).

See p. 15.

This is a meta-analysis of 59 cohort studies; not a Singapore figure.

Further, we assume RR is no different for diagnosed and undiagnosed folks (diagnosis slows down transition to frail, it does not reduce mortality)</doc>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless/Year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="relative risk mortality\nfrail diagnosed">
				<doc>Li, Yuelin, et al. &quot;Association of frailty and mortality risk in community-dwelling older adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis of 59 international prospective cohort studies.&quot; BMC Public Health (2026).

See p. 15.

This is a meta-analysis of 59 cohort studies; not a Singapore figure.

Further, we assume RR is no different for diagnosed and undiagnosed folks (diagnosis slows down transition to frail, it does not reduce mortality)</doc>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless/Year</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="age as a number" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<doc>Maps age dimension to a number</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="Effect of better\ncare after diagnosis">
				<doc>Idea is that it is 1 for those who are not well-managed; but it reduces for those who are well-managed</doc>
				<eqn>RR_of_transition_for_well_managed*proportion_well_managed +(1-proportion_well_managed)*1</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<stock name="resident population 1" access="input">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People</units>
			</stock>
			<aux name="total frail\ndiagnosed">
				<eqn>SUM(frail_diagnosed)</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="total frail\nundiagnosed">
				<eqn>SUM(frail_undiagnosed)</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="total pre-frail\ndiagnosed">
				<eqn>SUM(&quot;pre-frail_diagnosed&quot;)</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="total pre-frail\nundiagnosed">
				<eqn>SUM(&quot;pre-frail_undiagnosed&quot;)</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="Total 55 plus">
				<eqn>SUM(resident_population_1[*,*,57:102])</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="total frail">
				<eqn>total_frail_diagnosed + total_frail_undiagnosed</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="total pre-frail">
				<eqn>&quot;total_pre-frail_diagnosed&quot;  + &quot;total_pre-frail_undiagnosed&quot;</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="frail percent">
				<eqn>100*total_frail/Total_55_plus</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="pre-frail percent">
				<eqn>100*&quot;total_pre-frail&quot;/Total_55_plus</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<stock name="robust\npeople" access="output" isee:autocreated="true">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>resident_population * (1 - initial_frailty_prevalence - Initial_prefrailty_prevalance)</eqn>
				<inflow>ageing_in_robust</inflow>
				<inflow>net_inmigration_robust</inflow>
				<inflow>births_into_robust</inflow>
				<outflow>&quot;transition_robust_to_pre-frail&quot;</outflow>
				<outflow>deaths_robust</outflow>
				<outflow>ageing_out_robust</outflow>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People</units>
			</stock>
			<aux name="Initial prefrailty prevalance">
				<doc>(Correction needed -- incidence starts at 55, initial prevalence zero below 60)


SOURCE
------
Vaingankar et al. (2017), Geriatrics &amp; Gerontology International, 17(10): 1444-1454.
Nationally representative sample, n = 2,102 Singapore residents aged 60+.
Frailty assessed using Fried&apos;s physical frailty phenotype (5 criteria).

AGE-STRATIFIED PREVALENCE FROM RESULTS SECTION (p.4)
------------------------------------------------------
                     Frailty    Pre-frailty   Robust (implied)
  Age 60-74 years :   3.5%        37.9%          58.6%
  Age 75-84 years :  12.3%        47.5%          40.2%
  Age ≥85 years   :  24.6%        53.4%          22.0%

Note: these three bands sum to 100% by construction (Robust = 1 - Frail - Prefrail).

EXTENSION TO MODEL AGE BANDS
-----------------------------
The model covers single-year age cohorts from NewBorn to Age100andOver,
with frailty stocks active from age 55 onwards (Age_55_plus_vector = 1
for ages 55-100+, 0 otherwise).

Age 0-54  : initial_frailty_prevalence = 0
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence = 0

Age 55-59 : No Vaingankar data available (survey started at age 60).
            Assumption: prevalence equals the 60-74 band values,
            i.e., frailty = 3.5%, pre-frailty = 37.9%.
            Rationale: frailty is rare below 60 and the 60-74 band
            is already dominated by the 60-64 sub-group, making it
            a conservative upper bound for ages 55-59.

Age 60-74 : initial_frailty_prevalence      = 0.035
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence   = 0.379

Age 75-84 : initial_frailty_prevalence      = 0.123
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence   = 0.475

Age 85+   : initial_frailty_prevalence      = 0.246
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence   = 0.534

NORMALISATION
-------------
The three prevalence values (robust + pre-frail + frail) must sum
exactly to 1.0 for each cell. Checking against Vaingankar:

  60-74 :  0.586 + 0.379 + 0.035 = 1.000 ✓
  75-84 :  0.402 + 0.475 + 0.123 = 1.000 ✓
  85+   :  0.220 + 0.534 + 0.246 = 1.000 ✓

No normalisation adjustment required.

APPLICATION IN STELLA
----------------------
These prevalence values are applied uniformly across all race and
gender dimensions within each age band, as Vaingankar reports no
statistically significant race differences in frailty prevalence
(p = 0.022 at bivariate level but not retained in the adjusted
regression), and no significant sex difference in frailty
(p = 0.082, Table 1).

  INIT frail_undiagnosed    = resident_population * initial_frailty_prevalence
  INIT pre-frail_undiagnosed = resident_population * Initial_prefrailty_prevalence
  INIT robust_people        = resident_population * (1 - initial_frailty_prevalence
                                                       - Initial_prefrailty_prevalence)

The diagnosed stocks (frail_diagnosed, pre-frail_diagnosed) are
initialised at zero, consistent with the assumption that no
screening programme existed at the 2010 simulation start date.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="initial frailty prevalence">
				<doc>(Correction needed -- incidence starts at 55, initial prevalence zero below 60)


SOURCE
------
Vaingankar et al. (2017), Geriatrics &amp; Gerontology International, 17(10): 1444-1454.
Nationally representative sample, n = 2,102 Singapore residents aged 60+.
Frailty assessed using Fried&apos;s physical frailty phenotype (5 criteria).

AGE-STRATIFIED PREVALENCE FROM RESULTS SECTION (p.4)
------------------------------------------------------
                     Frailty    Pre-frailty   Robust (implied)
  Age 60-74 years :   3.5%        37.9%          58.6%
  Age 75-84 years :  12.3%        47.5%          40.2%
  Age ≥85 years   :  24.6%        53.4%          22.0%

Note: these three bands sum to 100% by construction (Robust = 1 - Frail - Prefrail).

EXTENSION TO MODEL AGE BANDS
-----------------------------
The model covers single-year age cohorts from NewBorn to Age100andOver,
with frailty stocks active from age 55 onwards (Age_55_plus_vector = 1
for ages 55-100+, 0 otherwise).

Age 0-54  : initial_frailty_prevalence = 0
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence = 0

Age 55-59 : No Vaingankar data available (survey started at age 60).
            Assumption: prevalence equals the 60-74 band values,
            i.e., frailty = 3.5%, pre-frailty = 37.9%.
            Rationale: frailty is rare below 60 and the 60-74 band
            is already dominated by the 60-64 sub-group, making it
            a conservative upper bound for ages 55-59.

Age 60-74 : initial_frailty_prevalence      = 0.035
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence   = 0.379

Age 75-84 : initial_frailty_prevalence      = 0.123
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence   = 0.475

Age 85+   : initial_frailty_prevalence      = 0.246
            Initial_prefrailty_prevalence   = 0.534

NORMALISATION
-------------
The three prevalence values (robust + pre-frail + frail) must sum
exactly to 1.0 for each cell. Checking against Vaingankar:

  60-74 :  0.586 + 0.379 + 0.035 = 1.000 ✓
  75-84 :  0.402 + 0.475 + 0.123 = 1.000 ✓
  85+   :  0.220 + 0.534 + 0.246 = 1.000 ✓

No normalisation adjustment required.

APPLICATION IN STELLA
----------------------
These prevalence values are applied uniformly across all race and
gender dimensions within each age band, as Vaingankar reports no
statistically significant race differences in frailty prevalence
(p = 0.022 at bivariate level but not retained in the adjusted
regression), and no significant sex difference in frailty
(p = 0.082, Table 1).

  INIT frail_undiagnosed    = resident_population * initial_frailty_prevalence
  INIT pre-frail_undiagnosed = resident_population * Initial_prefrailty_prevalence
  INIT robust_people        = resident_population * (1 - initial_frailty_prevalence
                                                       - Initial_prefrailty_prevalence)

The diagnosed stocks (frail_diagnosed, pre-frail_diagnosed) are
initialised at zero, consistent with the assumption that no
screening programme existed at the 2010 simulation start date.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="Age 55\nvector">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<flow name="deaths robust">
				<doc>Alternative

MAX(deaths-&quot;deaths_pre-frail_diagnosed&quot;-deaths_frail_undiagnosed-deaths_frail_diagnosed-&quot;deaths_pre-frail_undiagnosed&quot;,  0)

Note the missing link from robust population.

This flow is calculated such that total deaths in this module and in resident population module are equal.

Exaggerated frail and pre-frail relative mortality risk will cause this variable to be forced to 0 and result in imbalance.</doc>
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>   IF age_as_a_number[age] &gt;= 55
    THEN robust_people*relative_risk_mortality_robust
    ELSE deaths</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing in\nrobust">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF (age = age.Age100andOver) THEN ageing_out_robust[race, gender, age]
  ELSE IF (age = 1) THEN 0
  ELSE ageing_out_robust[race, gender, (age - 1)]</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing out\nrobust">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>one_by_year*robust_people</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing out pre-frail\nundiagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>one_by_year*&quot;pre-frail_undiagnosed&quot;</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing in pre-frail\nundiagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF (age = age.Age100andOver) THEN &quot;ageing_out_pre-frail_undiagnosed&quot;[race, gender, age]
  ELSE IF (age = 1) THEN 0
  ELSE &quot;ageing_out_pre-frail_undiagnosed&quot;[race, gender, (age - 1)]</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing out frail\nundiagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>one_by_year*frail_undiagnosed</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing in\nfrail undiagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF (age = age.Age100andOver) THEN ageing_out_frail_undiagnosed[race, gender, age]
  ELSE IF (age = 1) THEN 0
  ELSE ageing_out_frail_undiagnosed[race, gender, (age - 1)]</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing out\npre-frail diagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>one_by_year*&quot;pre-frail_diagnosed&quot;</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing in\npre-frail diagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF (age = age.Age100andOver) THEN &quot;ageing_out_pre-frail_diagnosed&quot;[race, gender, age]
  ELSE IF (age = 1) THEN 0
  ELSE &quot;ageing_out_pre-frail_diagnosed&quot;[race, gender, (age - 1)]</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing out\nfrail diagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>one_by_year*frail_diagnosed</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<flow name="ageing in\nfrail diagnosed">
				<dimensions>
					<dim name="race"/>
					<dim name="gender"/>
					<dim name="age"/>
				</dimensions>
				<eqn>IF (age = age.Age100andOver) THEN ageing_out_frail_diagnosed[race, gender, age]
  ELSE IF (age = 1) THEN 0
  ELSE ageing_out_frail_diagnosed[race, gender, (age - 1)]</eqn>
				<non_negative/>
				<units>People/Years</units>
			</flow>
			<aux name="total robust 55 plus">
				<eqn>SUM(robust_people[*,*,57:102])</eqn>
				<units>People</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="robust percent">
				<eqn>100*total_robust_55_plus/Total_55_plus</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="RR of transition\nfor well managed">
				<doc>
Serra-Prat, M., Sist, X., Domenich, R., Jurado, L., Saiz, A., Roces, A., Palomera, E., Tarradelles, M., &amp; Papiol, M. (2017). Effectiveness of an intervention to prevent frailty in pre-frail community-dwelling older people consulting in primary care: a randomised controlled trial. *Age and Ageing*, 46(3), 401–407. https://doi.org/10.1093/ageing/afw242

**Exact location of the RR = 0.46 figure:**

Page 403, Results section, second paragraph:

&gt; &quot;Frailty incidence was 0.40/100 person-years in the intervention group and 0.88/100 person-years in the control group, resulting in an RR of 0.46 (95% confidence interval [CI]: 0.20–1.04).&quot;

The same finding is also visible in **Table 2** (page 405), first row under Functionality: frail vs non-frail — 11 (15.3%) control vs 3 (4.9%) intervention, adjusted OR 0.23 (95% CI: 0.06–0.91), P = 0.036.</doc>
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
			<aux name="proportion\nwell managed">
				<eqn>0</eqn>
				<units>Dimensionless</units>
			</aux>
